javascript/jquery: get event target element on touchmove and mousemove
By HTML5WOOD On June 14, 2014 In How To
Events “touchmove” and “mousemove” do not have “target” property but we can get that by “document.elementFromPoint(from, to)”.event target for touchmove:
$('.navigation').on('tochmove', function (e) {
var target = document.elementFromPoint(e.touches[0].pageX, e.touches[0].pageY);
});
event target for mousemove:
$('.navigation').on('mousemove', function (event) {
var target = document.elementFromPoint(event.pageX, event.pageY);
});
jQuery/css: make any element unselectable
By HTML5WOOD On June 14, 2014 In How To
Sometimes, we face issue with selection on drag, mousedown and other events. Selection can be disable on any element by jquery and css as well.jQuery:Bind the events mousedown, keydown and selectstart on the element and return false value will make disable selection on that element.
$('.unselectable').live('selectstart mousedown keydown', function () {
return false;
});
css:There is property -user-slect in css that determines whether a user can select the content of an element. If value of this property is as “none” then user can not select any content of element .
.unselectable {
-webkit-user-select: none;
/* Chrome all / Safari all */
-moz-user-select: none;
/* Firefox all */
-ms-user-select: none;
/* IE 10+ */
}
For below IE 10, there is an attribute “unselectable” and it’s value should be as “on”:
<div unselectable="on"> you can't select me.</div>
jQuery: Bootstrap input field not getting focus in ios/android
By HTML5WOOD On June 14, 2014 In How To
Sometimes Bootstrap override the default behavior of elements. Because of this, I had faced an issue with input field that it does not capture focus on devices.Solution:event.stopPropagation() worked magically for this problem.
$("#myInputField").on("focus", function (event) {
event.stopPropagation();
});
